 investment has systemic benefits. Participants (50) will select from a menu of research related activities over 18 months: &lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>four 2-day research conferences on methodologies, eg evaluation of social work services 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>support groups to meet 6 times in groups of 10, led by social work faculty Professor Donald Forrester (University of Bedfordshire), Professor Susan White (Birmingham University), Professor David Shemmings (Kent University), and Dr. Claudia Bernard (Goldsmiths College, University of London) 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>mini-research placements offered to participants involving 12-24 days of supervised involvement at research centres/universities with interdisciplinary research teams starting January 2011 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>a website with the information needed, eg onference programmes, placement descriptions, reading resources 
&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>a writing retreat in June 2011 for participants who wish to protect time and attention in a supportive environment for writing research papers or bids. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>The project director is Professor of Social Work Research, Dr. Lynn McDonald, Middlesex University, London.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>78478</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Ongoing Engagement of Mid-Career Social work Academics based on the original grant ES/H023402/1</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>FAA4071A-E836-4AFE-9FC2-195D9BAEB493</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Social work continues to face threats to its funding and educational curriculums. In various forums, I have been able to refer to this project research findings from ES/H023402/1 funded by RDI/ESRC. The published documentation of the impact of the funded research to support research activities for mid career social workers, and two special edited research journal issues which reported the results of this ESRC project in 2012 and 13, have had a much more significant impact on the profession as well as on students as well as on the public, than we might have anticipated. Through the APSW Association of Professors of Social Work and the Research Division of SWEC (Social Work in Education), I have been able to promote this research project, and suggest policies and strategies for HEI. I wish that we could actually put the publications into open access for everyone to read.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>56d09db918fb51.35618078</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><